Interesting question, Jeff.


I really doubt the importance of phonetic orthography in reading speed, 
at least with mature, avid readers who are well past the sounding-it-out 
stage. And I imagine the length of some words in German might slow 
things down a bit--it&#39;s better to have *Fahrvergn�gen* than 
*Hoffnunglosigkeit* in your *G�tterd�mmerung! *

I had a Russian professor tell me that because Russian letters have very 
few descenders and ascenders, it makes it harder to read than English.  
If I recall, one of the reasons Read designed the tall and deep letters 
the way he did was to increase the number of descenders/ ascenders for 
easier reading. (But dyslexics got the shaft!)

Another thing that might be interesting to consider would be grammatical 
redundancy, do inflected languages, where the gender, number and case of 
nouns and adjectives have to match read faster than those like English 
with few grammatical endings, or does the redundacy get in the way?

I have a suspicion that the alphabetic languages which might be most 
difficult would be Hebrew and Arabic, since in ordinary printed 
material, vowels are not indicated. A lot more has to be inferred by 
context than in European languages. Anyone know of any studies yea or nay?

